@NODE "Usage"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Usage
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    @{b}@{u}Starting/Stopping:@{uu}@{ub}
    CyberLemmings can be started from both WB and CLI, and can be stopped
    by sending a CTRL-C to it, or by starting it twice.

    @{b}@{u}Arguments/Tooltypes:@{uu}@{ub}

    * BACKDROP - If enabled, lemmings will collide with windows that have
      the backdrop flag set, by default they don't. Can be combined with
      BORDERLESS if needed.

    * BORDERLESS - If enabled, lemmings will collide with windows that have
      the borderless flag set, by default they don't. Can be combined with
      BACKDROP if needed.

    * FRAMERATE - Can be set to an integer between 0-10, where the default
      value is 4. Specifying 0 will give you animation without synching,
      while 1 will try to give you full framerate. Specifying 2 will
      display the lemmings at 50%, 3 will give you 25%, and so on.

    * GFXDIR - A string that specifies in what directory CyberLemmings will
      look for image-data. By default this is set to "PROGDIR:gfx/".

    * GFX - Is a string that sets what gfx-set should be used, it is set
      to @{i}"Standard"@{ui} as default. To se what gfx-sets are included
      with the package, look in the gfx/ directory.
   
    * INACTIVSCR - CyberLemmings doesn't move or animate the lemmings if
      the currently active screen is not the wb screen, there are two
      reasons for this, the first being that it might save valuable
      cpu-time. The second because it can sometimes produce gfx-corruption
      on the currently active screen, if something is drawing on a screen
      behind the active one. If you still want lemmings to be animated even
      if the wb screen isn't active, set this, note that it might introduce
      the side-effects mentioned above if you do.

    * LEMMINGS - Specifies how many lemmings should be drawn to the wb
      screen. Can be set to a value between 1-500, where the default is
      3.

    * NOTELEPORT - Disable teleporters, if they are supported by the
      selected gfx-set. Teleporters are for example used by the worms2
      gfx-set and can enable the worms to teleport into "pockets" made up
      by windows.

    * NOTITLEBAR - If enabled, lemmings won't collide with "titlebar
      windows". "Titlebar windows" are windows that have their top border
      in the screen-title. This feature is nice if you for example want to
      view a big picture and display it in a window on the wb screen. If
      the window then fills the whole screen (or just a part of it from top
      to bottom) and this option is enabled, lemmings wont collide with it,
      ignoring it completely.

    * OCCUPIED - Enable occupied feature, if it is supported by the
      selected gfx-set. Used in the worms2 gfx-set, where worms sometimes
      take out a skipping-rope and jump for a while :).

    * PUSHER - Enable pusher feature, if it is supported by the
      selected gfx-set. Used in the updated "Standard" and "X-Mas" gfx-sets.
      With this enabled the characters sometimes decide to push a window
      that they bump into!

    * RANDOMDEATH - Lemmings randomly die. This is good to enable if you
      want to keep all the lemmings from getting stuck at the bottom of
      the screen.

    * RANDOMTURN - Lemmings randomly turn around when walking.

    * SOUND - Enable sound/sound-events (AHI). :)
    
    * TASKPRI - Sets the task-priority. This is an integer between
      -128-127. A task-priority of @{b}atleast@{ub} -30 is recommended
      if you want to keep CyberLemmings from stealing cpu time from other
      tasks. The default value here is -32.
    
    * USEWTOF - Use WaitTOF() instead of WaitBOVP().

@ENDNODE

