@NODE "IncSets"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Included gfx-sets
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

All gfx-maps have to support fallers, walkers and diers, apart from that,
they can support other modes, here follows an explanation of every gfx-map
included. (And the supported modes apart from the required ones)

There is also a list of @{"contributed" link ContSets} gfxmaps.

@{b}Nudie@{ub} - This is a girl that walks around the wb and occasionally
flashes herself ;) (But ONLY if you have "OCCUPIED" set). The detail isn't
very high in this gfx-map. (If you wan't to make a porn app out of this
you'll have to draw it all yourself.)
Supports: occupiers.
Sounds: @{u}None@{uu}.

@{b}Standard@{ub} - Theese are the standard lemmings from Lemmings 1. (Or
atleast they are very similiar to them).
Supports: gliders, climbers, pushers.
Sounds: die, start. (#?.8svx)

@{b}Worms2@{ub} - Theese are the worms from Worms2/Worms Armageddon.
Supports: teleporter, occupier.
Sounds: die, teleport, walk. (#?.8svx)

@{b}X-Mas@{ub} - Theese are the standard lemmings from Lemmings 1 wearing a
santa-claus outfit...
Supports: gliders, climbers, pushers.
Sounds: die, start. (#?.8svx)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ContSets"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Contributed gfx-sets
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

@{b}Qweek@{ub} - This is a yellow blob made by Nowee. A very charming
gfx-map with a Matrix-like teleportation anim.
Author: Nowee
Supports: occupiers, teleporter.
Sounds: @{u}None@{uu}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "OwnSets"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Making your own gfx-sets
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    Below follow some chapters that will guide you in the creation of
    your own gfx for CyberLemmings.

    If you make a nice gfx-map please @{b}do@{ub} @{"send it to me" link Author} and I will include
    it in the next CyberLemmings distribution.

    8.1. @{" T " LINK GFXMap}he GFXMap.prefs file.
    8.2. @{" D " LINK Drawing}rawing custom graphics.
    8.3. @{" H " LINK Soundfiles}ow to include your own sound-files.

    Here is a list of all available images, you only include the ones
    that you support, naturally; see the @{"GFXMap.prefs" LINK GFXMap} to see what options
    you have.
    climb.chunky
    die.chunky
    fall.chunky
    glide.chunky
    occupy.chunky
    push.chunky
    teleport.chunky
    walk.chunky

    If you still don't know how to go about creating your own gfx-set,
    @{"mail me" link Author} or look in the preview/ dirs of the included gfx-sets,
    for examples.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "GFXMap"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 GFXMap.prefs
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    This file includes all the information telling CyberLemmings how many
    frames each file in the gfx-set contains and how fast the lemmings
    move around the screen. This is how @{i}Gfx/Standard/GFXMap.prefs@{ui} looks:

    0. @{i}1.1]    ;Minimum version of CyberLemmings required...@{ui}
    1. @{i}16]     ;Width.@{ui}
    2. @{i}16]     ;Height.@{ui}
    3. @{i}2,4,3]  ;Faller.     Speed         Frames  Offset@{ui}
    4. @{i}1,5,4]  ;Glider.     Speed SFrames Frames         X=Unsupported.@{ui}
    5. @{i}1,8,2]  ;Walker.     Speed         Frames  Offset@{ui}
    6. @{i}1,8,4]  ;Climber.    Speed         Frames  Offset X=Unsupported.@{ui}
    7. @{i}9]      ;Dier.                     Frames@{ui}
    8. @{i}X]      ;Teleporter.               Frames         X=Unsupported.@{ui}
    9. @{i}X]      ;Occupied.         SFrames Frames  Offset X=Unsupported.@{ui}
   10. @{i}1,8,4]  ;Pusher.     Speed         Frames  Offset X=Unsupported.@{ui}

      The "]" character basically means: Stop fetching here.

      0: Minimum version of CyberLemmings required for this gfx-map, plain
         and simple.

    1/2: Width/Height of each frame in pixels. Yes, all animations must
         have the same size within the same gfx-map.
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      3: This is the initial mode the lemmings have when first appearing on
         screen.
         @{b}Speed=2@{ub}, means the lemmings will fall two pixels each frame when
         they are in "falling mode".
         @{b}Frames=4@{ub}, means @{i}Gfx/Standard/fall.chunky@{ui} consists of 4 images.
         Moreover the "Frames" keywords have the same meaning everywhere, so we
         will not mention it anywhere else than here.
         @{b}Offset=3@{ub} means that the lemmings will be moved 3 pixels to the
         direction they are walking, before starting to fall.
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      4: Gliders are activated after they have fallen down more than 1/4 of
         the screensize. @{b}Can be disabled by specifying "X".@{ub}
         @{b}Speed=1@{ub}, means they will fall one pixel each frame.
         @{b}SFrames=1@{ub}, is the number of "start-frames" used for gliders,
         theese frames will be displayed only when the glider feature is
         activated. SFrames has the same meaning everywhere.
         The actual number of frames in the image is Frames-SFrames when
         there is an SFrames parameter. So if you have 10 frames where 2 of them
         are SFrames... You have 2 SFrames and 8Frames = 10 Frames.
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      5: @{b}Speed=1@{ub}, means characters will move 1 pixel each frame when
         walking. As you see Speed always means the number of pixels moved
         each frame... So we stop discussing it... ;)
         @{b}Offset=2@{ub}, specifies the number of pixels the lemming is moved
         forward each time it turns. This has been added to eliminate
         collision problems.
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      6: The climbers @{b}can be disabled by specifying "X".@{ub}
         @{b}Offset=4@{ub}, specifies the number of pixels from the border of each
         frame to the nearest colideable pixel. Without this set correctly
         lemmings won't climb properly. Setting it wrong will cause the lemmings
         to climb to far from the window or collide with it. (or not climb at all)
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      7: Displayed when lemmings die... Simple ;).
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      8: Teleporters are useful if climbers aren't included. Why not have
         both btw? Teleporters @{b}can be disabled with "X".@{ub}
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

      9: The occupied feature is something that is enabled randomly. In
         the worms2 gfx-map for example, the worms jump with a
         skipping-rope. @{b}Can also be disabled by specifying "X".@{ub}
         @{b}Offset@{ub}, specifies the "collision offset of CyberLemmings.
         In worms2 this is for example 8, this to enable the worm to
         jump with his skipping rope. Putting it simple it means that the
         gfx has a 8 pixel boundary before it leaves its "collision state".
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.0 AND ABOVE@{ub}

     10: The pushers @{b}can be disabled by specifying "X".@{ub}
         @{b}Offset=4@{ub}, specifies the number of pixels from the border of each
         frame to the nearest colideable pixel. Setting this wrong will cause
         pushers not pushing the windows correctly.
         @{b}AVAILABLE IN 1.1 AND ABOVE@{ub}

         @{b}NOTE!!:@{ub}
         If you are doing a gfxmap with only the first 0-9 entries (1.0 version)
         just dont add the 10'th entry at all... (And set the required version
         to 1.0). If you want pushers, add the 10'th line and set 1.1 as the
         required version!

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Drawing"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Drawing custom graphics
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    The current version of CyberLemmings doesn't have support for datatypes
    currently, only 32bit ARGB chunky images. So you draw the images in a
    paint program like Personal Paint or Deluxe Paint, and then just
    convert them to 32bit ARGB chunky format with a program like ArtPro or
    similiar.

    There are some guidelines you should follow:

    Try keeping the image-graphics at the bottom of each frame. @{"Here" link "CyberLemmings_wr.iff/main"} is
    an example of what I mean. This is essential if you want the collision
    checking of CyberLemmings working properly. Also as another note,
    every pixel not colour 0 ($AA000000) will be checked for collision.
    Pixels that are in the colour $AA000000 are always "transparent" when
    outputed on the screen! Other coulours are "solid".

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Soundfiles"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 How to include your own sound-files
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    This is very flexible in CyberLemmings. Every single "starting" event in
    CybeLemmings can have its own sound (If the gfx-map supports that
    particular event). If any of the files below can be found in the gfx-map
    directory, the corresponding sound/event is enabled. Theese are the
    possible events, and how they work:

    @{b}climb.8svx@{ub} - Played when character starts climbing.
    
    @{b}die.8svx@{ub} - Played when character dies. (Like when a window is moved
    over him)
    
    @{b}fall.8svx@{ub} - Played when character starts falling after it walks of
    a window, or if the user moves a window away from it's feet.

    @{b}glide.8svx@{ub} - Played when a character starts "gliding". (In the
    Lemmings case this is when they take out their umbrella)

    @{b}occupy.8svx@{ub} - Played when character gets "occupied".

    @{b}push.8svx@{ub} - Played when a character decides to push a window.
    
    @{b}start.8svx@{ub} - Played when the character first appears ontop of the
    screen when CyberLemmings is started and if it was just killed and has
    been repositioned at the top again.
    
    @{b}teleport.8svx@{ub} - This sample is played twice when played, first when a
    character teleports away and then when it appears at its new position also.
    
    @{b}walk.8svx@{ub} - Played when characters start walking after they have been
    falling, climbing or gliding.

    Take note that the sounds are played @{u}ONCE@{uu} each time an event for
    a particular character occurs. As you might have guessed the samples have
    to be in IFF-8SVX format. The frequency/period of the sample is fetched
    directly from the file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Other"

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Some other software under development.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

    * Hamster - DirectConnect/eDonkey port for AmigaOS. (known as AmiDC)
      @{i}Not yet released.@{ui}

    * Project 42 - A packer (without a name, as of now) that packs archives
      both faster and better than lzx.
      @{i}Not yet released.@{ui}

    * WarpSDL.library - A media library originaly from the Linux world.
      This is not a port, but a re-implementation of the API, desgined and
      optimized for AmigaOS.
      @{b}It is available on my homepage.@{ub}

    * MusicMix.library - Is a music-library API using AHI. It has support
      for custom sound-format plugins. With this library, software can have
      support for numerous sound-formats while also making sure supporting
      more formats in the future... Currently supports MP3, OGG, MOD and XM.
      If a piece of software supports one of theese formats, it can also
      use the others. Without changes!
      @{i}Not yet released.@{ui}

    * XMasBench - Gives your workbench the christmas feel, this software
      was developed by me and Martin Ejdestig some time ago. @{b}It is available
      on Aminet.@{ub}

@ENDNODE
